<h3>Configure the environment</h3>

<p>
  Before building an app you need to configure environment variables to let Buck know the locations of Android SDK and Android NDK.
</p>

<p>
  First of all, check for existing variables:
</p>

{literal}
<pre>
$ env | grep ANDROID_
ANDROID_HOME=&lt;path-to-sdk&gt;
ANDROID_NDK_REPOSITORY=&lt;path-to-ndk&gt;
ANDROID_SDK=&lt;path-to-sdk&gt;
</pre>
{/literal}

<p>
  Set the missing variables to the locations of Android SDK and Android NDK or set the paths in your {call buck.concept_buckconfig /} file.
</p>

<p>
  Before building make sure you installed correct build tools and a target in Android SDK and correct version of Android NDK. You can find the required versions of these tools in {call buck.concept_buckconfig /}:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>See {call buckconfig.android_build_tools_version /} to get the version of build tools in Android SDK.</li>
  <li>{call buckconfig.android_target /} points to the target.</li>
  <li>{call buckconfig.ndk_version /} points to the version of Android NDK.</li>
</ul>

Optionally:

<ul>
  <li>{call buckconfig.android_sdk_path /} is an absolute path to the Android SDK.</li>
  <li>{call buckconfig.ndk_path /} is an absolute path to the Android NDK.</li>
  <li>
    {call buckconfig.ndk_repository_path /} is an absolute path to a
    directory that contains multiple Android NDKs in subdirectories.
    Buck selects which NDK to use based on the value of 
    the {call buckconfig.ndk_version /} property in <code>.buckconfig</code>.
  </li>
</ul>

<h3>Build the Android sample</h3>

<p>
  In order to build the app, you use the {call buck.cmd_build /} command, specifying your app as the target. The target may be defined in the {call buckconfig.alias /} section in the {call buck.concept_buckconfig /} file or it would be the name of your Android project prepended by <code>//[the directory where your project is located]:</code> (e.g., <code>//android:demo-app</code>).
</p>

{literal}
<pre>
# From the root `cross-platform-scale-2015-demo/` directory
# demo_app_android is an alias in .buckconfig for //android:demo-app. Either works.
buck build demo_app_android
</pre>
{/literal}

